  isbn = {979-8-3503-1469-4},
  publisher = {IEEE},
  abstract = {The air quality of the surrounding area needs to be monitored and air needs to be purified if air quality levels exceed a certain level. The recent developments in technologies allow for combining different types of devices into a single device. In the past few years, more people have been aware of air quality indoors and outdoors. This study aimed to design an Internet-of-Things (IoT) system to detect humidity, PM2.5, and temperature and determine the air quality. The air purifier sent the essential data to the user via Wi-Fi. The system collected data from various sensors such as DHT22 and PMS5003. The current indoor air quality was evaluated to determine standard indoor air quality values. Fuzzy logic was used to accurately evaluate the level of air quality based on the data and the standard values and control the fan’s power of the air purifier. The air purifier effectively eliminated airborne particles and filtered dust particles and smoke. The prototype built for this research was compared with two different types of commercially available air purifiers in terms of size and cost. A t-test was used for comparison. The prototype’s t-score was 0.242 which was below the critical value of 2.101. Statistically, in the time of filtering the air in an enclosed environment, there were no significant differences between the commercial air purifiers and the prototype.},
