  abstract = {The purpose of this research is to develop a system that provides real-time alerts to the residents of Mandalay in the event of hazardous air quality conditions, enabling prompt awareness and response to potential health risks. In addition to Carbon-dioxide levels at Mandalay Technological University (MTU), key urban CO2and suburban areas of Mandalay, including major transportation hubs like highway bus terminals and train stations, are monitored. CO2 conditions in these areas are monitored and analyzed using TTGO Call ESP with Wi-Fi modules microcontrollers and DM118 CO2 sensor. The DM118 offers continuous CO2 measurement, providing real-time data, which is crucial for applications. This feature supports dynamic environmental monitoring where timely responses to air quality changes are essential. A solar energy system as a renewable power source is utilized in the research. The data from DM118 CO2 sensor is transmitted to the ESP32 microcontroller, displayed on a 16*2 LCD display with I2C interface and uploaded to the PythonAnywhere cloud server for remote monitoring and analysis of air quality in real-time. The CO2 data from three locations in Mandalay for October 2024 were obtained from the PythonAnywhere server, downloaded as CSV files and analyzed and compared using charts. The accuracy was calculated by comparing the values measured by ECD MDY.},
