  abstract = {Smart agriculture has come out as a key solution to improve productivity and sustainability in modern farming. This paper presents the design and MATLAB-based simulation of an IoT-enabled smart greenhouse monitoring and control system. The system continuously monitors five critical environmental parameters temperature, soil moisture, humidity, light intensity, and CO2 concentration using simulated sensor data. To monitor and manage environmental conditions, we set specific threshold values for each parameter. When a value goes beyond its limit, it triggers an alert and automatically activates suitable actions like turning on fans, water pumps, and artificial lights. The system tested this setup using a dataset of 100 time-series samples to achieve accuracy in the proposed results under different environmental conditions. According to the simulation, temperature was the most unstable, which generated 58 alerts. Soil moisture and humidity followed with 52 and 46 alerts. In comparison, CO2 levels and light intensity were closer to their optimal ranges, generating just 29 and 17 alerts. On the basis of sensor input, the system automatically manages the unsuitable conditions on the occurrence of any alert. To review the system, the model used graphs and pie charts. This research gives a strong base to build a real-time smart greenhouse solution using IoT to increase productivity and sustainability. The main objective of this research is to support small farmers and sustainable agriculture.},
