  issn = {1558-4127},
  publisher = {IEEE},
  abstract = {When flames start in residential areas, near industrial sites, or in forested areas, everyone’s safety and the environment are in danger. A coordinated smoke and fire monitoring strategy and quick response are required to minimize damage and disaster effects. This study presents the CSMEWRS system, which stands for Consumer Safety Monitoring and Early Warning Response System”, and has been developed explicitly for drone fire detection. Specifically, we’re looking at AI-enabled drones with thermal imaging cameras, many sensors, and algorithms for deep learning. Real-time fire and smoke detection are accomplished via custom built CNN based image detectors. At the same time, RNN is used to analyze the data collected from environmental sensors, including air quality and temperature. The drones fly over high-risk areas for wildfires and keep an eye on them at all times. The AI will immediately notify response teams and send troops to the fire scene as soon as it is detected. Accurate information regarding the fire’s location and severity allows for a quicker reaction from the team. The system has demonstrated remarkable effectiveness across various situations, particularly in outside mobility settings where it achieves high detection rates. Its versatility and scalability make it ideal for multiple uses, including forest fire prevention, industrial safety monitoring, and home fire prevention. The technology above outperforms traditional approaches thanks to its superior early warning capabilities. Similarly, our work offers a chance to lessen the impact of a major disaster by incorporating drones equipped with AI into the relief effort before, during, and after the event.},
