  abstract = {Nowadays, people are physically and mentally affected due to stress which has become a significant public health concern. A machine learning (ML)-based framework is presented in this study to classify human stress levels based on physiological and behavioral parameters. A secondary dataset containing 200 samples has been used, including the 5 key features: heart rate, sleep duration, screen time, physical activity and caffeine intake. Stress Levels were classified into 3 classes which are low, medium and high based on the predefined rules. The three supervised machine learning models in this study are used which are Decision Tree, Support Vector Machine (SVM) and Artificial Neural Network (ANN). These models are created and trained on the dataset. Further, the performance of the models is evaluated through testing data. The dataset is divided into two parts i.e., training data and testing data in the ratio of 80:20. While SVM offered clear linear decision boundaries, the Decision tree model gave simplicity and interpretability. The ANN model comprising of \$\\mathbf\{1 0\}\$ neurons demonstrate strong ability to learn difficult, non-linear patterns between the characteristics. Supported by 2D and 3D visualization, confusion matrices and prediction accuracy were applied to evaluate the outcomes. This work shows how Artificial Intelligence methods could be used in behavioral monitoring and healthcare.},
